      "writtenOn": "2017-04-04T14:36:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "both BlitThreadOpCode and BlitThreadCmd are implementation details of the BlitThread class. I would recommend moving these under the private section of the latter class, as well as use an num class, e.g.:\n\n  class BlitThread : ... {\n  public:\n      ....\n  private:\n      enum class Opcode {\n          Init \u003d 0,\n          Blit \u003d 1,\n          Post \u003d 2,\n          SetWsCb \u003d 3,\n          Exit \u003d 4,\n      };\n\n      struct Cmd {\n          Opcode op \u003d Init;\n          FenceSync* sync \u003d nullptr;\n          HandleType windowSurface \u003d 0;\n          HandleType colorBuffer \u003d 0;\n      };\n\n      ...",
      "revId": "e28ffa55a933210ae6614576b6ba7bf3fe66434c",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "247c7d7e_5086a46e",
        "filename": "android/android-emugl/host/libs/libOpenglRender/BlitThread.h",
        "patchSetId": 8
      },
      "lineNbr": 39,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000411
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-04-04T14:36:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I would recommend providing default initializers for all members here, this would prevent sending crap from the stack from one thread to the other during requests. Another alternative is to always initialize local variables with {} as in:\n\n    BlitThreadCmd cmd \u003d {};\n    cmd.opCode \u003d ...;\n    etc\n\nI don\u0027t think this is going to solve your problem but at least it will make the code more robust.",
      "revId": "e28ffa55a933210ae6614576b6ba7bf3fe66434c",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
